channel.name: TypeError: Cannot read properties of null (reading 'fetchAccount')

messages.content: Struggling a bit with my pages directory of a zkApp. On npm run dev, have a working UI but when I go to interact with anything, I get this error message about the fetchAccount function. I assume its something fairly trivial but haven't been able to troubleshoot myself. Any help would be appreciated. I have only used the fetchAccount function in the index.page, zkappworker, and zkappworkerclient files within ui/src/pages.
Can you share more of the index.tsx file?
Been trying to update this previous zkapp called ConcealedCare that uses old o1js code etc.
Here’s the whole index.page.tsx
@DFST   i changed my const res to match your formatting and it didn't seem to work
still getting the same error
Have you added fetchAccount to import?
yeah
Check the value of publicKey!
i.e. the public key in contracts/keys ?
Seems like mina.requestAccounts() should not work with Berkeley, only local.
Just do console.log("Public key",  publicKeyBase58)
You can also try to import Mina and see the value of Mina.hasAccount(publicKey!)
yeah i think ive possibly got things confused as am doing npm run dev and attempting to run on berkeley, but also have a demo.ts file within src for local deployment
will debug myself then work out whats going on
thanks for your help @DFST
You can try to switch to local blockchain and make it work, then switch to Berkeley providing private keys for accounts funded thru faucet
cheers thanks ill try locally - is that through npm run dev then?

Probably yes (don't see your repo), but you should also change the line 
```typescript
await zkappWorkerClient.setActiveInstanceToBerkeley();
```
@DFST am thinking about how to deploy on berkeley. What is the berkeley alternative for mina.requestAccounts() ?
still getting multiple strange cannot read properties of null (fetchAccount/createPublishAccomProofTransaction) functions

You will get on the deployer 49 MINA and will be able to reuse it by storing private key in env.json:
```typescript
console.log(deployer.toBase58())

...
import { DEPLOYER } from "../env.json";
deployer = PrivateKey.fromBase58(DEPLOYER);
```
See full examples on https://github.com/dfstio/minanft-lib/blob/master/test/berkeley.test.ts

messages.content: @DFST thanks so much this is v helpful. Not sure if I have an env.json file?

You can create it:
```typescript
{
  "DEPLOYER": "EK...",
  "MINAURL": "https://proxy.berkeley.minaexplorer.com/graphql"
}
```
and i assume it just goes in the ui folder?
usually at the root folder of you project, just make sure that path is right
